SALMONELLOSIS, SEROTYPE HADAR - USA: LIVE POULTRY CONTACT
*********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 23 Jul 2012
Source: UPI [edited]
http://www.upi.com/Health_News/2012/07/23/Salmonella-outbreak-linked-to-live-poultry/UPI-54491343100297/


USA health officials said on Mon 23 Jul 2012 that [another] multistate outbreak of human salmonella infections has been linked to live poultry.

Officials at the CDC in Atlanta said a total of 37 people were infected with the outbreak strain of _Salmonella [enterica_ serotype] Hadar in 11 states: Arizona, California, Colorado, Idaho, Illinois, Oregon, Tennessee, Texas, Utah, Washington and Wyoming. 37 percent of people ill were children age 10 or younger; 8 people were hospitalized, but no deaths were reported.

Epidemiologic, laboratory and traceback findings linked the outbreak of human salmonellosis to contact with live poultry from Hatchery B in Idaho, CDC officials said.

"Mail-order hatcheries, agricultural feed stores and others that sell or display chicks, ducklings and other live poultry should provide health-related information to owners and potential purchasers of these birds prior to the point of purchase," CDC officials said in a statement. "This should include information about the risk of acquiring a salmonellosis from contact with live poultry."

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Once again, small animals such as chicks, ducklings, mice, and baby turtles are not uncommon vehicles for salmonellosis for 2 reasons: they are small enough to handle, and they carry salmonellae. Two ways to minimize the risk: aggressive hand washing after contact and choose other pets such as dogs or cats. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1hiS.]
